{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509525"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:17:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:17:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11429"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11429"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.62,0.02,0.09,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4062"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44722"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4062"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29600"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1092"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42601"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44722"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of increasing chest pain which radiates into his neck. The pain came on after an evening spent with his friends, eating pizza, drinking, and snorting cocaine. He has not had any nausea or vomiting but indicated that he felt like coughing after his cocaine use. His only health issue is a history of asthma and he is not on any medications. He does not have any allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 100/72 mmHg, pulse 104/min, temperature 37.2\u00b0C, respiratory rate 24/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2 \u003C/sub\u003E96% on room air. Precordial examination reveals systolic crepitations and reduced heart sounds. There are no palpable masses and no signs of airway compromise. An ECG is unremarkable and a chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumomediastinum secondary to asthma","Drug-induced pneumomediastinum","Right basal pneumothorax","Boerhaave\u0027s syndrome","Cocaine-induced pericarditis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a recent history of chest pain which radiates into his neck, mild hypotension, tachypnoea, and tachycardia on a background of drug use. The examination findings also reveal the \u2018Hamman sign\u2019 which is an auscultatory finding associated with mediastinal emphysema. This clinical picture is suggestive of a diagnosis of\u00a0a \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumomediastinum;\u003C/strong\u003E which is confirmed by the presence of radiolucent streaks in the mediastinum on the chest X-ray. The X-ray also shows air tracking up into the neck (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth spontaneous pneumothoraxes and pneumomediastinum have been identified in users of cocaine (both intranasal users and smokers). This kind of barotrauma is theorised to be the result of habitual practices like performing a Valsalva manoeuvre after inhalation or forcefully exhaling forcefully into each other\u0027s mouths paired with inflammation and fibrotic parenchymal changes which result from routine drug use. Given the lack of otherwise noteworthy history and clinical findings the \u003Cstrong\u003Emost likely diagnosis is drug-induced (i.e., cocaine) pneumomediastinum\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u00a0Other options:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumomediastinum secondary to asthma: \u003C/strong\u003EThis describes secondary pneumomediastinum which occurs as a result of underlying airway disease like COPD, asthma, and/or cystic fibrosis. The patient is a non-smoker and has no notable personal or family history of lung disease making this an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight basal pneumothorax: \u003C/strong\u003EGas in the pleural space is termed a pneumothorax. Risk factors for primary spontaneous pneumothoraces include subpleural blebs, smoking (cigarette, cannabis), genetic predisposition, and changes in atmospheric pressure. On the other hand, secondary pneumothoraces occur in the presence of underlying lung disease, most commonly COPD/emphysema. A pneumomediastinum can develop as a consequence of a pneumothorax, but the diagnosis of a pneumothorax is supported by the identification of a white visceral pleural line, on chest radiography, that defines the interface between the lung and pleural air. These features are absent in this case and another cause is more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoerhaave\u0027s syndrome (spontaneous oesophageal perforation):\u003C/strong\u003E describes an oesophageal perforation that typically occurs due to a sudden increase in intra-oesophageal pressure combined with negative intrathoracic pressure. This scenario classically occurs with severe straining or vomiting, excessive coughing, retching, or laughing \u2013 all of which are absent in the above scenario. Despite similar radiographic findings (mediastinal or free peritoneal air and/or subcutaneous emphysema), there would also be a pleural fluid collection, containing undigested food.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECocaine-induced pericarditis:\u003C/strong\u003E Pericarditis can cause chest pain similar to that of pneumomediastinum. Other findings include reduced heart sounds and corresponding ECG changes (ST elevation or PR depression). The evaluation of a patient with chest pain following cocaine ingestion should include a history and physical, 12-lead ECG, imaging and radiological studies, and serial biomarkers (i.e., troponins). Despite the presence of cocaine ingestion, the lack of suggestive ECG findings and cardiac biomarkers makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pneumomediastinum is commonly diagnosed on a CXR; it appears as radiolucent streaks in the mediastinum."],"references":["Triadafilopoulos, G. 2021. Boerhaave syndrome: Effort rupture of the esophagus, UpToDate. [online] uptodate.com. Available at: \u003Chttps://www.uptodate.com/contents/boerhaave-syndrome-effort-rupture-of-the-esophagus\u003E [Accessed 11 Dec 2021]","Spontaneous pneumomediastinum. 2012. Australian Journal for General Practitioners, 38, 413-414. Available from \u003Chttps://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2009/june/spontaneous-pneumomediastinum\u003E","Mechem, CC. 2021. Pulmonary complications of cocaine use, UpToDate. [online] uptodate.com. Available at: \u003Chttps://www.uptodate.com/contents/pulmonary-complications-of-cocaine-use\u003E [Accessed 11Dec 2021]"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29600"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11429"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"13007"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20435"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"13007","links":{"self":"https://app.